\f1 March 20,
\f0  1726
\f2\b \
\
Today is the anniversary of the birth of Sir Isaac Newton
\f3\b0  (1642-{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Style_and_New_Style_dates"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 1726}}), English {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 physicist}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 astronomer}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theologian"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theologian}} who is widely recognised as one of the most influential scientists of all time and as a key figure in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_revolution"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 scientific revolution}}. His book {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophi%C3%A6_Naturalis_Principia_Mathematica"}}{\fldrslt 
\f4\i \cf4 Philosophi\'e6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica}} (
\f4\i Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy
\f3\i0 ) laid the foundations of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 classical mechanics}}. Newton also made seminal contributions to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 optics}}, and shares credit with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz}} for developing the infinitesimal {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 calculus}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 In 
\f4\i Principia
\f3\i0 , Newton formulated the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_laws_of_motion"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 laws of motion}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_law_of_universal_gravitation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 universal gravitation}} that formed the dominant scientific viewpoint until it was superseded by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_relativity"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theory of relativity}}. Newton used his mathematical description of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravity"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 gravity}} to prove {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler%27s_laws_of_planetary_motion"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Kepler's laws of planetary motion}}, account for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tide"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 tides}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trajectory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 trajectories}} of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comet"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 comets}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axial_precession"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 precession of the equinoxes}} and other phenomena, eradicating doubt about the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_System"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Solar System}}'s {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heliocentrism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 heliocentricity}}. He demonstrated that the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamics_(mechanics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 motion of objects}} on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Earth}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomical_object"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 celestial bodies}} could be accounted for by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 same principles}}. \
In addition to his work on calculus, as a mathematician Newton contributed to the study of power series, generalised the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_theorem"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 binomial theorem}} to non-integer exponents, developed {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_method"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 a method}} for approximating the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero_of_a_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 roots of a function}}, and classified most of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_plane_curve"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 cubic plane curves}}.\cb1 \
\
\
\uc0\u55357 \u56524  20 marzo 1726\
\
Oggi \'e8 l'anniversario della morte di Sir Isaac Newton (1642-1726), matematico, fisico, astronomo e teologo inglese, ampiamente riconosciuto come uno degli scienziati pi\'f9 influenti di tutti i tempi e come figura chiave della rivoluzione scientifica. Il suo libro Philosophi\'e6 Naturalis Principia Mathematica (Principi matematici di filosofia naturale) ha gettato le basi della meccanica classica. Newton ha anche dato contributi fondamentali all'ottica e condivide con Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz il merito di aver sviluppato il calcolo infinitesimale.\
\
Nei Principia, Newton formul\'f2 le leggi del moto e della gravitazione universale, che costituirono il punto di vista scientifico dominante fino a quando non furono superate dalla teoria della relativit\'e0. Newton utilizz\'f2 la sua descrizione matematica della gravit\'e0 per dimostrare le leggi di Keplero sul moto dei pianeti, spiegare le maree, le traiettorie delle comete, la precessione degli equinozi e altri fenomeni, eliminando i dubbi sull'eliocentricit\'e0 del sistema solare. Dimostr\'f2 che il moto degli oggetti sulla Terra e dei corpi celesti poteva essere spiegato con gli stessi principi. \
\
Oltre al lavoro sul calcolo, come matematico Newton contribu\'ec allo studio delle serie di potenze, generalizz\'f2 il teorema binomiale a esponenti non interi, svilupp\'f2 un metodo per approssimare le radici di una funzione e classific\'f2 la maggior parte delle curve piane cubiche.\
